<h1 style="text-align:center">Deployment of <strong><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">E</span></span><span style="color:#000099"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">asy</span></span><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">C</span></span><span style="color:#000099"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">oder</span></span></strong> scripts</h1><p><span style="color:#660000"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">E</span></strong></span><span style="color:#000099"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">asy</span></strong></span><span style="color:#660000"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">C</span></strong></span><span style="color:#000099"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">oder</span></strong></span> scripts are quite easily deployed as real websites. There are a number of ways to do it, as follows:</p><h2>Script in BODY</h2><p>The simplest approach is to embed your script in the HTML of the page. The basic outline is</p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;html lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;head&gt;</span></span></p><p style="margin-left:40px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;meta charset=&quot;UTF-8&quot;&gt;<br />&lt;meta name=&quot;viewport&quot; content=&quot;width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0&quot;&gt;<br />&lt;title&gt;My scripted web page&lt;/title&gt;<br />&lt;script type=&#39;text/javascript&#39; src=&#39;/easycoder/easycoder.js&#39;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;/head&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;body&gt;</span></span></p><p style="margin-left:40px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;pre id=&quot;easycoder-script&quot;&gt;</span></span></p><p style="margin-left:80px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">alert `Hello, world!`</span></span></p><p style="margin-left:40px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;/pre&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;/body&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;/html&gt;</span></span></p><p>In the above, the <span style="color:#660000"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">E</span></strong></span><span style="color:#000099"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">asy</span></strong></span><span style="color:#660000"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">C</span></strong></span><span style="color:#000099"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">oder</span></strong></span> main JavaScript library is included in the HEAD and the script you wish to run is placed inside a special preformatted block inside the BODY. Any of the scripts you write in the editor can be used, without any changes being needed.</p><h2>Script in HTML</h2><p>The second technique is to add a script to an existing HTML page. As in the first example, the script will be in its own preformatted block but there will be other HTML on the same page. The location of the script in the page is not significant; it can be at the top, in the middle or at the bottom.</p><p>The main difference is that instead of the script creating DOM elements as in the tutorials, these will in many cases already exist. So instead of using <span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">create</span></span> you will use <span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">attach</span></span>, giving the id of the element you want to attach to:</p><p style="margin-left:40px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">create Button in Container</span></span></p><p>becomes</p><p style="margin-left:40px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">attach Button to `ec-button`</span></span></p><p>This technique saves a small amount of code but in a large page it can be quite difficult to find an element in the HTML. The most common use is probably where an existing page is being retrofitted with script.</p><h2>Script from REST</h2><p>Here the script is not embedded in the page at all. Instead, all that is present is a &#39;boot loader&#39; that retrieves the script by making a call to a REST server. A PHP server is included with <span style="color:#660000"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">E</span></strong></span><span style="color:#000099"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">asy</span></strong></span><span style="color:#660000"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">C</span></strong></span><span style="color:#000099"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">oder</span></strong></span> so there&#39;s very little to do. Here&#39;s what the simplest form of this page looks like:</p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;html lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;head&gt;</span></span></p><p style="margin-left:40px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;meta charset=&quot;UTF-8&quot;&gt;<br />&lt;meta name=&quot;viewport&quot; content=&quot;width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0&quot;&gt;<br />&lt;title&gt;My scripted web page&lt;/title&gt;<br />&lt;script type=&#39;text/javascript&#39; src=&#39;/easycoder/easycoder.js&#39;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;/head&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;body&gt;</span></span></p><p style="margin-left:40px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;pre id=&quot;easycoder-script&quot;&gt;</span></span></p><p style="margin-left:80px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">variable Script<br />rest get Script from `_load/myscript`<br />run Script<br />stop</span></span></p><p style="margin-left:40px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;/pre&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;/body&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;/html&gt;</span></span></p><p>Here the script is located in the root directory. If you want to place it somewhere else you put the full path where the word <span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">myscript</span></span> is, replacing all forward slashes (/) with tilde (~) characters. If you can deal with the CORS issues you can use a complete URL to retrieve your script from a remote site.</p>